sixthPage <- tabPanel(
  "Report Page",
  
  fluidRow(
    column(
      12,
      tags$h3("Affiliation:"),
      tags$p("INFO-201: Technical Foundations of Informatics - The Information School - University of Washington"),
      tags$h3("Date:"),
      tags$p("Winter 2022"),
      tags$h3("Abstract:"),
      tags$p("Racial stereotypes have existed long before the film industry due to colonialism. Many depictions of non-white characters on film were root in racial biases and cultural ignorance.Cinematic stereotypes reflect and shape common prejudices. Perceptions can be influenced by portrayals of Asians as nerdy, black men as dangerous and Latinas as fiery."),
      tags$h3("Keywords:"),
      tags$ul(
        tags$li("Stereotypes"),
        tags$li("Cinema"),
        tags$li("Racism"),
        tags$li("Sexism"),
        tags$li("Society")
      ),
      tags$u(h3("1.0 Introduction:")),
      tags$p("Stereotypes regarding race and gender are a big issue in western media. Not only does this affect the youth and their growing perspectives on people in society, it also encourages adults to continue to stereotype. Due to the spread of misinformation through the media, there have been multiple incidences where these stereotypes have been used against many individuals. There are multiple examples of shows targeting the youth which have many stereotypes. One example of this is the show Jessie on Disney Channel. The show includes four kids who are adopted and live with a nanny. There is an Indian boy, an African American girl, a white boy, and a blonde girl. The Indian boy is shown as weak and nerdy with an Indian accent. The African American girl is shown as rebellious and sassy. The white boy is shown as athletic and the blonde girl is shown as dumb and boy obsessed. "),
      tags$u(h3("2.0 Design Situation:")),
      tags$p(strong("Framing the topic of concern. What is the topic of concern, problem domain or design situation?")),
      tags$p("The topic of concern which we hope to gain more knowledge, and data for is the stereotyping of gender and race through western media."),
      tags$p(strong("What are the key elements of the topic?")),
      tags$p("The key elements of stereotypes found in Television, Movies, and Advertisements are racism, discrimination, bias, and bullying."),
      tags$p(strong("What are the key scientific, cultural, social, governmental, or economic issues or questions?")),
      tags$p("The key social issues and impacts of stereotyping is that many individuals may be discriminated against due to another individuals false perception of them. Through watching media at a young age, many individuals may imprint an idea or an impression of a group of people due to the way they are shown in cinema. Implicit bias can also occur due to the imprinted idea of certain groups with a common identity. Unknowingly, seeing similar characters with similar characteristics in media over and over again can cause an audience to view those individuals and categorize all of them in that way."),
      tags$p(strong("Human values")),
      tags$p("The human values that are connected to the western media's perception of gender and people of color,  are inclusion and respect. These values originate with the idea of appealing to a greater audience, and allowing more individuals to connect with positive perceptions of people of their same identity groups. Media is supposed to inspire all individuals, especially western media which appeals to a diverse audience."),
      tags$p(strong("Stakeholders")),
      tags$p("Direct Stakeholders regarding stereotypes and creating characters in western media are writers, character artists, directors and producers. These individuals are motivated by creating a project for a greater audience which will allow all people to be able to relate and feel inspired by the characters. The indirect stakeholders are the audience watching the media. They are indirect stakeholders because they are affected by the change through a switch in perspective of individuals as well as those minority groups who are usually stereotypes in media will start to face less bias and discrimination."),
      tags$p(strong("Benefits and Harms")),
      tags$p("There could be a lot of benefits and harms with interventions taken to get rid of stereotypes in Hollywood. Bringing in more diversity into the film industry to get more individuals to look over character creations and story productions will allow for a decline in privilege hazard, bias, and racism when creating characters for a greater audience. Some harms of this could be many individuals disagreeing with what is racist and what is not or what is okay to put and what is not because there is not really a right or wrong answer. Some unanticipated consequences could be that some individuals could feel that the diversity is too forced and the media has become to progressive too fast. Some individuals may also feel like due to sudden change they don't enjoy the media as much because of how careful, sensitive and unrelatable."),
      tags$u(h3("3.0 Research:")),
      tags$ol(
        tags$li("How many individuals of different ethnicities think it's important to get rid of stereotypes of race in the media?"),
        tags$li("How do stereotyped characters in media affect people of different ages?"),
        tags$li("How many people feel as though it is not important at all to have an accurate representation of their identity?"),
      ),
      tags$p("Stereotypes are generalizations that are assigned to groups of people. These groupings can be by race, class, gender, religion, country of origin, etc. The generalizations (whether negative or positive) are used to confine a group to others' standards and expectations. Our media and film contribute heavily to the perpetuation of stereotypes. By showcasing generalizations and presenting them as common concepts, they become mainstream ideas. We haven't completely gotten away from these stereotypes in movies but there are strides being made. These questions are to show that the stereotypes seen on tv and film can manifest in real life. This is because people will internalize what they've seen or don't see in their lives. People can be mistrusted and mistreated because of the stereotype associated with their group; racial profiling young black men is a contentious issue in the United States, while people perceived as Muslim, some of whom were in fact adherents to other faiths, were treated degradingly following the September 11th terrorist attacks. We are able to combat this by adding more inclusion and diversity. They have found that prejudices breaks down when people of various ethnic groups have increased contact with each other. A sociologist by the name of Nancy Wang Yuen said that \"Racism, in the form of job exclusion and racially stereotyped roles, has defined the Hollywood film industry since its birth in the early 1900s\" _(Reel Inequality: Hollywood Actors and Racism)_. 
"),
      tags$u(h3("4.0 The Dataset See Design:")),
      tags$p(strong("When deciding what movie to watch, how important are the following? The movie avoids racial stereotypes.")),
      tags$p(strong("When deciding what movie to watch, how important are the following? All of the actors are the same race as the characters they are portraying.")),
      tags$p(strong("Do you agree or disagree with the following statements? I see accurate representations of my racial or ethnic identity in movies.")),
      tags$a("https://morningconsult.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/190524_crosstabs_HOLLYWOOD_Adults_v1.pdf"),
      tags$p("This data comes from an online survey which received 2,201 responses, all of which were of at least 18 years of age. This survey asked the questions above relating to the stereotyping and race of characters in media. In this survey, one observation equates to one person's response to this question. When answering each question, respondents picked between five options: \"very important,\" \"somewhat important,\" \"not that important,\" \"not important at all,\" and \"don't know/no opinion,\" or in the case of the third question, the equivalent for how much the respondent agrees with the statement. These responses are grouped based on the participant's race, ethnicity, religious beliefs, employment status, age, political standing, and more. In other words, many people from vastly different backgrounds are represented in this dataset."),
      tags$p("This data was collected by The Hollywood Reporter and Morning Consult, and published by The Morning Consult, in May 2019. While not explicitly stated, the purpose of the study as a whole seems to be to gauge how people of different religious, political, and employment backgrounds consume media and partake in various lifestyles. Considering the involvement of The Hollywood Reporter, the data collection effect was likely funded by that publication so that they could better share the study's findings as a part of their news offerings, and make more accurate conclusions about the state of the industries in question. Therefore, The Hollywood Report is likely to benefit from the data, as it improves their ability to make justifiable claims about various entertainment industries. Moreover, this dataset may give THR more ideas for news to publish, meaning that they will likely make money from the data. Unfortunately, it is hard to confirm whether the data is completely reliable and trustworthy, as the online survey format allows people to easily provide false information for the data collectors. More specifically, the source I linked states: \"Results from the full survey have a margin of error of plus or minus 2 percentage points.\" However, the sample size appears large enough that individual errors are not likely to change anyone's analysis of the data, nor is it likely to lead our group to reach false conclusions in the making of this project. I obtained this data through the website statista, which linked to the far more extensive pdf we will use for our project. I found the aforementioned statista page by searching for information on racial stereotypes in google's dataset search website."),
      tags$u(h3("5.0 Findings:")),
      tags$p("Through the data gathered, there are many patterns noticed about how many individuals of different demographics feel about the way their own identities and other identities are portrayed in western media. There are characters of women as well as individuals of different races which are constantly being stereotyped in the media. About 76% of people of color believe that there needs to be accurate representation of their race in western media. It is incredibly important to have accurate representation of race in the media. Individuals who watch movies and tv shows and see the stereotyped characters repeatedly will start to get this perception about that group of people, and start to create bias unknowingly. About 27% of Generation Z and 19% of Millennials feel that it is important to get rid of stereotypes. The issue and awareness of stereotypes in the media has become bigger in younger generations. Due to more awareness of racism and sexism and the root of their problems, individuals of younger generations are able to point out problems within society. About 16% of females and 17% of males feel as though it is important for film to have accurate representation of characters. In all, several individuals of all demographics feel that stereotypes in media are a major societal issue and can cause problems in all aspects of life. Many agree that it is important to have accurate information about groups of people in order to create real change in society. Additionally, removing any stigma around groups of individuals will allow for all audience members to have an authentic experience of the media they are watching."),
      tags$u(h3("6.0 Discussion:")),
      tags$p("Through the information we have gathered about the stereotypes in media and the effects they have on multiple individuals, we realize the importance of diversity in all aspects of behind the scenes of filming. From creating the ideas to editing the film, there must be individuals with a range of identity characteristics in order to reduce bias and stereotypes. Additionally, this will allow for all audience members to relate and feel as if they are being properly represented by the characters and their story. One of the biggest issues regarding stereotypes in media is that the individuals who are creating the characters don't realize the characters they are making are stereotyped. There are deeper meanings regarding stereotyped characters that some people don't realize can cause a negative outlook on a demographic. For example, the black best friend, the Asian supermarket owner, the feisty Latina women, or the tech nerd Indian. It's important to get rid of these stereotypes and the only way to do so, or catch any bias within the making of the characters and a storyline is to have diversity within the western media. Additionally, it is important to understand that stereotypes may not be as apparent, or we may not realize the media has negative meaning towards a certain demographic. Audiences of all age groups and all demographics are affected by the media. Individuals who watch many movies with the same type of character with the same identity, will start to get the idea that all individuals are like this."),
      tags$u(h3("7.0 Conclusion:")),
      tags$p("Everyone or all age groups watch some form of media. The repetitive patterns of the same type of character cause many audience members to believe and unknowingly create bias towards those individuals who share those same characteristics. It is important to have diversity in all fields and all workforces. By getting rid of stereotypes of individuals of different genders and races, the view of those individuals will begin to change. The bias and discrimination with hiring in the workforce will begin to decrease. In conclusion, it is so important to have diversity in the western entertainment industry."),
